Add specific harmful content warnings to Ephemera Folders
Redesign the preservation status indicators on the resource show page

comments.body: @hackartisan thank you. I'm not sure this would be the appropriate place to list the last checked fixity date, but I'm curious about why you think that. Isn't the most important thing to the user that it gets fixed? "Repair this file" would simply fix the problem by regenerating derivatives, or re-preserving the master/primary file. If both local and cloud fixity are broken, then the user would have to re-upload the file. What other options would there be?

figgy.title: UI Use Case: Fixity check has failed, how do I fix it?

comments.body: How does a re-preserve action work? Does it pull whichever version passed the most recent fixity check and replace the failed version with that one? If both are broken, does that mean that our preservation system failed and they have to locate (or re-digitize) and re-ingest the original object?

At today's standup, I heard an explanation for why we have the steps @tpendragon listed above. I'm uneasy that we are building this system and checklist/workflow primarily as a way to catch race condition errors. Are we not able to prevent race conditions through file locking, or other means? Also, if manually checking the metadata file is part of the workflow, is that the first step?

Also, I'm assuming running a fixity check can take some time. If that's the case, they will need to kick each fixity check off and then come back later. Being able to step through the tasks and fix it right away would be a better experience. Is it possible to run the fixity check on both before the user arrives at this page? Perhaps triggered by the original fixity failure that brought them to this screen?

Also, a user is not just looking at a file, they are making a judgement. The above workflow assumes they will be able to see a difference. What if they look identical to the naked eye, but have some subtle variation that is not noticeable? How do they select the file that was intended?
